questions.question: Can we have world peace with a for-profit arms industry?
Are blockchains a revolutionary technology or a technological revolution?

landing: My name is Matthew Gurman. I'm currently a backend engineer at {SeedFiLink}. My favorite {CuisineLink} is Mexican. I love music that makes me feel strong emotions. I like to shoot film {PhotographyLink} as a hobby. Oh, and I love to ask {QuestionsLink} and {ThinkDeeplyLink} about things interest me. Please make yourself comfortable, and don't hesitate to reach out via email or text!

message.p1: My favorite thing about film is how every shot counts. You only get so many in a roll - it's inherently different than digital in that regard. I apprecaite how techinical it is. There's this phenomenon with technology where as it gets more advanced, the user loses their intuition for how it was engineered. With a film camera from the 80s, it's remarkably simple. I enjoy hearing the 'click' when I take a picture and manually cranking the film forward. It gives me this feeling that somehow I'm more of a photographer. Lol. Something only an amatuer would say.
message.p2: The pictures always have this 'snapshot in time' feel to them that I never get with digital. And of course all of these images have special meaning to me, as they were taken during memorable moments throughout my life. So I hope you enjoy them, and eventually I will add a commenting feature - feedback would be amazing.

pictures.description: This picture was taken during a homestay I did in the northern mountains of Vietnam. Aside from it being one of the most beautiful natural environments Iâ€™d ever been in, the people there were outstandingly generous, engaging and full of life. The boy in this picture was the son of our hosts, and he was frankly inspirational. His energy and enthusiasm for life perfectly embodied the wonder of being a child. And he was so happy to spend time with the guests. Here is he taking a break and enjoying a coca-cola.

pictures.description: The hike to the top of Clouds Rest is not easy, and the final 100 meters are perhaps the scariest. You can see my sister Jo trekking across the thin ridge of rocks to reach the panoramic views at the summit. Itâ€™s hard to overstate the ecstasy all the hikers were feeling. We had all just hiked 7 miles up a 2,000 foot mountain and were taking in a 10/10 360 degree view of Yosemite. It was so easy to be friendly and make conversation. And the PB & J I enjoyed was one of the best of my life.
pictures.title: Clouds Rest
